ninkrijk","Beaford, Devon, England":"Beaford, Devon, England"},"en":{"Abt 1399–":"about 1399–Deceased","1330–Male":"1330–Deceased","1368–1404":"1368–1404","1399–Male":"1399–Deceased","1402–Female":"1402–Deceased","1336–Female":"1336–Deceased","1340–Female":"1340–Deceased","1342–Female":"1342–Deceased","1348–Female":"1348–Deceased","1355–1404":"1355–1404","1350–1420":"1350–1420","1352–Female":"1352–Deceased","about 1380":"about 1380","1352":"1352","1330":"1330","1340":"1340","1350":"1350","1404":"1404","1348":"1348","1336":"1336","1402":"1402","1368":"1368","Abt 1399":"about 1399","1355":"1355","1399":"1399","1420":"1420","1342":"1342",", Devonshire, England":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","Beaford, Devon, England":"Beaford, Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hatch","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Hatch (Bedfordshire, Devon, Hampshire, Somerset, Wiltshire), Hacche in South Molton (Devon), or else a topographic name from residence near a hatch, a gate leading to a forest or sometimes a sluice-gate, from Middle English <i>hacche</i> ‘gate’ (Old English <i>hæcce</i>, Kentish Old English <i>hec(c)</i>). This name has been in Ireland since the 17th century, associated with County Meath and the nearby part of Louth."],"variants":[{"name":"Hedge","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone who lived by a hedge or enclosure, from Middle English <i>hegge</i> ‘hedge, fence’. In the early Middle Ages, hedges were not merely dividers between fields, but had an important defensive function when planted around a settlement or enclosure.","English: probably also a variant of   Hatch  , with voicing of the final consonant.","Americanized form (translation into English) of German   Hecke  ."]},{"name":"Hatcher","meanings":["English (southern): topographic name for someone who lived by a gate, from Middle English <i>haccher(e)</i>, a derivative of <i>hacche</i> ‘gate’. This normally denoted a gate marking the entrance to a forest or other enclosed piece of land, sometimes a floodgate or sluice-gate. Compare   Hatch  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Hatch was born about 1399, in Devon, England, United Kingdom, his father, William Hatch, was 50 and his mother, Jane Worlington, was 48. He had at least 1 son and 4 daughters with Maud Leigh."},"et":{"Abt 1399–":"umbes 1399–Surnud","1330–Male":"1330–Surnud","1368–1404":"1368–1404","1399–Male":"1399–Surnud","1402–Female":"1402–Surnud","1336–Female":"1336–Surnud","1340–Female":"1340–Surnud","1342–Female":"1342–Surnud","1348–Female":"1348–Surnud","1355–1404":"1355–1404","1350–1420":"1350–1420","1352–Female":"1352–Surnud","about 1380":"umbes 1380","1352":"1352","1330":"1330","1340":"1340","1350":"1350","1404":"1404","1348":"1348","1336":"1336","1402":"1402","1368":"1368","Abt 1399":"umbes 1399","1355":"1355","1399":"1399","1420":"1420","1342":"1342",", Devonshire, England":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Beaford, Devon, England":"Beaford, Devon, England"},"fi":{"Abt 1399–":"noin 1399–Kuollut","1330–Male":"1330–Kuollut","1368–1404":"1368–1404","1399–Male":"1399–Kuollut","1402–Female":"1402–Kuollut","1336–Female":"1336–Kuollut","1340–Female":"1340–Kuollut","1342–Female":"1342–Kuollut","1348–Female":"1348–Kuollut","1355–1404":"1355–1404","1350–1420":"1350–1420","1352–Female":"1352–Kuollut","about 1380":"noin 1380","1352":"1352","1330":"1330","1340":"1340","135